## Limitations

- Cosine similarity over TF-IDF measures lexical/keyword overlap, not deep semantic understanding — a correct answer phrased very differently from the model answer can score lower than it deserves
- Transcription errors from speech recognition propagate directly into the evaluation score
- A single stored "model answer" may not capture all valid ways of correctly answering a question

## Future Improvements

- Move toward embedding-based semantic similarity (e.g., sentence embeddings) to better handle paraphrased correct answers
- Support multiple acceptable model answers per question
- Add audio preprocessing/noise reduction to improve speech recognition robustness across accents and recording conditions
- Run a rigorous before/after study with logged data to validate time-saving and accuracy claims

## Notes on Reported Metrics

The ~20% time-reduction and ~15–20% accuracy-improvement figures referenced in this README are estimates based on the expected difference between manual and automated evaluation, not results from a formal, controlled measurement study with logged before/after data. If republishing or citing this project, it's worth running an actual timed comparison (manual evaluators vs. the automated system on the same batch of answers) to confirm and report exact, reproducible numbers.

## Disclaimer

This project is intended as a first-pass automated assessment aid, not a full replacement for human evaluators. Its similarity score reflects keyword/semantic overlap, not deep conceptual understanding, so nuanced or partially correct answers still benefit from human review.

